06167nam a22008175i 9781487595678DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191966onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875956787 a10.3138/97814875956782doi  a(DE-B1597)513676  a(OCoLC)1091715135  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aQE501b.C66 1966eb 7aSCI0300002bisacsh04a551.4/100aContinental Drift /ced. by G. D. Garland. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1966  a1 online resource (156 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tContributors -- tPart I: Current Ideas on Continental Drift -- tSome Rules for Continental Drift -- tMantle Properties and Continental Drift -- tThe Rock Magnetic Evidence for Continental Drift -- tThe Ancient Flora and Continental Drift -- tAstronomical Evidence on the Present Rate of Continental Drift -- tPart II: Evidence on Continental Drift from the Arctic and Eastern Seaboard of Canada -- tDevelopment of Submarine Physiography in the Canadian Arctic and Its Relation to Crustal Movements -- tMorphological and Geophysical Studies on the Eastern Seaboard of Canada: The Nova Scotian Shelf -- tUnderwater Gravity Measurements in the Gulf of St. Lawrence -- tThe Cabot Fault Zone -- tMaps0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe possibility that the continents of the earth have undergone major changes in position during the earth's history has fascinated scholars for at least three hundred years. Recently, evidence from several scientific disciplines has shown that the possibility must be very seriously considered in any study of the surface features of the earth. The first part of this volume consists of papers given at a symposium on continental drift, held at the annual meeting of the Royal Society of Canada in Charlottetown in June 1964. They present the views of three geophysicists, a botanist, and an astronomer. In these papers, the present evidence for or against continental drift is reviewed and the authors in most cases draw their own conclusions. The reader will find that there is not unanimous agreement in favour of drift. Nearly all discussions of continental drift stress the possible separation of the Americas from Europe and Africa. Considerable work has been done on the tracing of structures, on each side of the Atlantic Ocean, which might once have been connected. Geologists and geophysicists working in the Arctic or on the eastern seaboard of Canada have an important contribution to make to this subject. The second part of this volume, therefore, consists of a group of papers, also presented at the Charlottetown meeting, which throw light on the complicated crustal structure of these regions. In any attempt to reconstruct North America as part of Europe the features described in these papers will have to be taken into account. Once again, the reader will find differences of opinion on the question of whether the evidence favours a separation of our continent from Europe. Indeed, it is because the theory of continental drift us so difficult to confirm without ambiguity by direct observation that it remains controversial but exciting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aContinental drift. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh1 aBerger, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanchard, J. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, H. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCok, A. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutsch, Ernst R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/